gomodel:SYNGO_2886  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.2: \"Detection of HSP70 and Hsp40 in the PSD fractions prepared from various parts of the rat brain\"\n- \"The distribution of HSP70 and Hsp40 in the PSD fraction was further examined in the fractions prepared from rat cerebral cortex, hippocampus and cerebellum. All PSD fractions examined contained p73 and Hsp40 but not p72 Fig. 2\"\n\nFig.7: \" Localization of HSP70 immunoreactivity in the synaptic areas at an electron microscopic level\"\n- \"Postsynaptic structures in the cerebral cortex and cerebellum were stained (Fig. 7). All or portions of PSDs in postsynaptic spines were stained. PSDs were immunoreactive but rather weak compared with regions of subsynaptic web. Postsynaptic structures of both axo-somatic and axo-dendritic synapses were positive for HSP70. Presynaptic terminals were also stained but less frequently than the postsynaptic structure (Fig. 7a). Either one of pre- or post-synaptic structure but not both of them in a single synapse was stained for HSP70. More than half of the synapses examined showed postsynaptic staining alone.\"\n\nNote: Hsp70 is not enriched in the PSD and is most abundant in the postsynaptic 'subsynaptic web. I have annotated to the general term 'postsynapse (GO:0098794)' to reflec the diffuse staining in the postsynapse.. Experimental description: - \"Subcellular fractions of the brain were obtained from Wistar rats 6 weeks old, unless otherwise stated \"\n- \"For immunohistochemical examination at the light microscopic level, brains from Wistar rats....For immunoelectron microscopy, tissues were fixed...\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-14" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_2886" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

<http://identifiers.org/rgd/621725>
